<font color="#FF0000">AWARDS</font><br>
<tt>Wed Feb 26 15:42:16 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I was a combat medic with a grunt unit in the 1st Cav Div. for a bit more that two years. I was not a C.O. and I DID carry a M-16. I used it the best I could when there was a need as, how I saw it, my role, my JOB, was to keep the men around me alive and in one piece by what ever means were available. If I could have, I would have carried an 175mm Howitzer on my back if it would have brought just one more back home. Just as I would blow away any son-of-bitch that wanted to do the same to my wife and daughter, I fired on those who wanted to do harm to those in my unit.<br><br>
The stories of the two C.O. medics cause me grief, I'm not sure why-in any case, they are better men than I. I remember the combat, I remember the cries for MEDIC!, and a shitload more.<br><br>
I am not going to apologize for my going to VN anymore. I am not going to allow anyone to make me feel guilt for the fact that I went or for those things that I have done while in-country. I came home to those who sent me, sent us, to a ungrateful, hostile nation that treated me, treated us, like garbage, dirt, shit for many, many years. This happened in spite, of what those like the blind, tunnel visioned, myoptic denials of the likes of nurse ratchet or lou cohan or whatever the fuck he wants to call himself today.<br><br>
To try and link the awards earned by our individual achievements to whether the war was wrong or not is an exercise in futility. No one that I know of ever got a medal for blowing away civilians. In all my time in-country, the only dead civilians were those killed by others. Awards such as bronze stars, silver stars, all the way up to the congressional medal of honor, are bestowed on those who risked their asses to save others, not for killing or adding to a body count.<br><br>
Doc, you wonder why vets are sensitive to how you expressed yourself or how you asked your questions?  For many of those who came home with their medals in there pockets, they learned real quick, to box them up and slide them under their beds and leave them to gather dust for years. The nation of two-face, ingrates and hypocrites forced them to. Those of us that had to write to the Dept. of Army to get our awards, waited for many, many years before doing so.  The only damn things that we came home with that could possibly be construed as positive was denied us. Some of us are just beginning to realize that there are value in these individual awards. We are just beginning to understand that we did some good, in our own individual way, by our individual acts. We have decided not to take the crap that we have endured for many years, and, in spite of our weariness of war, to stand up once again and do battle for what is ours.
<p><code>-- docdel@maui.net  (Doc Del) </code><p>


